Bring a #medium pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and slice @button mushrooms{8%ounce} into ¼-inch-thick pieces (skip if your mushrooms are
pre-sliced!). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add mushrooms;
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and slightly
crispy, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Wash out pan.

Pat @sirloin steak{14%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with salt and
pepper. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in #pan{} used for mushrooms over medium-high
heat. Add steak; cook to desired doneness, ~{3-6%minutes} per side. Turn off heat; transfer to a
#plate{}. Wash out pan.

Once water is boiling, add @cavatappi pasta{6%ounce} to #pot{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until
al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

While pasta cooks, melt @butter{2%tablespoon} in pan used for mushrooms over medium-high heat. Add
scallion whites and cook until just softened, ~{1%minute}.

Add @flour{1%tablespoon} and cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Whisk in @milk{6.75%ounce} and 1⁄3 cup reserved pasta cooking water, breaking up any flour clumps.
Simmer until slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> Use pan used for chicken or steak here.

Stir @cream cheese{2%tablespoon} into pan with sauce until melted and combined.

Stir in mushrooms, drained cavatappi, and @garlic herb butter{2%tablespoon}. Season with salt and
pepper.

> If needed, stir in more reserved cooking water a splash at a time until pasta
> is coated in a creamy sauce.

Thinly slice steak against the grain; stir in along with mushrooms.

Divide pasta between #bowls{} and sprinkle with @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup} and scallion greens. Serve.